{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"de3a0e24-89db-4616-bf3e-808dd34bd57e","content":"Here's the skip attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Example:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod]\n[Ignore(\"Waiting on bug #1234 fix\")]\npublic void MyMSTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Waiting on bug #1234 fix\")]\npublic void MyXUnitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test]\n[Ignore(\"Waiting on bug #1234 fix\")]\npublic void MyNUnitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test]\n[Skip(\"Waiting on bug #1234 fix\")]\npublic void MyTUnitTest() { }\n```\n\nKey differences: xUnit embeds the skip reason in the test attribute itself (`Fact`/`Theory`), while the others use a separate attribute. All four frameworks will report skipped tests distinctly from passes/failures in test results.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d8c5ce06-9bfe-4544-a334-ef4e30205dcf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the correct skip/ignore attributes for each of the four test frameworks. Let me provide this from my knowledge - this is a straightforward reference question.\n\nFor MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit:\n\n- **MSTest**: `[Ignore(\"reason\")]`\n- **xUnit**: `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]`\n- **NUnit**: `[Ignore(\"reason\")]`\n- **TUnit**: `[Skip(\"reason\")]`\n\nThis is a simple factual question - no need to invoke tools or skills.","outputTokens":450,"requestId":"4C10:3C82B9:E3A7F0:1199B90:6A012D7D"},"id":"ddaef9bb-6dea-48fb-bbbe-9a58f09b48d5","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:14:46.687Z","parentId":"c845c517-c240-495a-a536-12157e57faf7"}
